<section class="bm-section">
  <h2>The Most Underappreciated Longevity Marker on Your Standard Blood Panel</h2>

  <p>Serum albumin sits on virtually every comprehensive metabolic panel. It is routinely ordered, routinely reported, and routinely ignored. When it falls within the wide 3.5&#8211;5.0 g/dL reference range, most clinicians note it as normal and move on. This is a significant missed opportunity &#8212; because albumin, interpreted correctly, is one of the most informative longevity indicators available from a standard blood draw.</p>

  <p>The evidence for albumin as a longevity predictor is extensive and remarkably consistent across populations. A meta-analysis of over 100 prospective studies found that each 10 g/L (1 g/dL) decrease in serum albumin below 4.5 g/dL was associated with a 24% increase in all-cause mortality, a 38% increase in cardiovascular mortality, and a 56% increase in cancer mortality. <sup><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21487014/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">1</a></sup> These associations persist after adjusting for age, kidney function, liver disease, and virtually every other known confounding variable.</p>

  <p>Albumin predicts longevity more strongly than many celebrated cardiovascular risk factors. In elderly populations, it consistently outperforms LDL cholesterol, blood pressure, and even several disease-specific biomarkers as a predictor of 5- and 10-year survival. Yet almost no one knows their albumin level, and it is rarely discussed in longevity health conversations.</p>
</section>

<section class="bm-section">
  <h2>What Albumin Does: Functions Beyond "Just a Protein"</h2>

  <p>Albumin is the most abundant protein in the blood, constituting approximately 55&#8211;60% of total plasma protein. Its physiological roles are numerous and often underappreciated.</p>

  <p><strong>Oncotic pressure:</strong> Albumin is responsible for approximately 80% of the colloid osmotic (oncotic) pressure that keeps fluid within blood vessels rather than leaking into surrounding tissues. When albumin falls significantly, the reduced oncotic pressure allows plasma to leak into the interstitium &#8212; producing edema (swelling), ascites (abdominal fluid accumulation), and pleural effusions. This is the mechanism behind the characteristic swelling seen in severe malnutrition, liver disease, and kidney disease with proteinuria.</p>

  <p><strong>Transport protein:</strong> Albumin transports an enormous diversity of molecules through the bloodstream &#8212; including free fatty acids, thyroid hormones (particularly T4), cortisol, bilirubin, bile acids, calcium, magnesium, copper, numerous drugs (warfarin, aspirin, statins, benzodiazepines are all albumin-bound), and various metabolic waste products. When albumin is low, the free (unbound) fraction of these molecules rises &#8212; altering their bioavailability, biological activity, and metabolism.</p>

  <p><strong>Antioxidant:</strong> Albumin contains the single most reactive thiol group in plasma &#8212; the Cys-34 residue &#8212; which functions as the blood's primary reactive oxygen species scavenger. It accounts for approximately 80% of total plasma antioxidant capacity. Low albumin directly reduces the blood's antioxidant defense, contributing to the oxidative stress that accelerates vascular aging and cellular damage.</p>

  <p><strong>Anti-inflammatory:</strong> Albumin has intrinsic anti-inflammatory properties, binding pro-inflammatory lipid mediators and copper (which catalyzes free radical reactions). Its decline during inflammatory states creates a feedback loop in which lower albumin leads to greater oxidative and inflammatory burden, which further suppresses albumin synthesis.</p>
</section>

