  <p>Always interpret albumin alongside hsCRP. Because albumin is a negative acute-phase reactant &#8212; meaning it falls during inflammatory states &#8212; a low albumin with elevated hsCRP primarily reflects an inflammatory condition rather than protein deficiency or liver disease. A low albumin with normal hsCRP points more directly toward nutritional or hepatic causes. The combination of low albumin and elevated hsCRP is particularly prognostically concerning, as it reflects both active inflammation and the inability to maintain adequate protein status in the face of it.</p>
</section>

