<section class="bm-section">
  <h2>Albumin, Aging, and the Frailty Connection</h2>

  <p>The relationship between albumin and aging is bidirectional and self-reinforcing. Albumin levels tend to decline with age &#8212; both because chronic inflammatory burden increases and because protein synthesis capacity and dietary protein intake often decrease in older adults. This declining albumin is not merely a biomarker of aging; it actively contributes to the processes that accelerate frailty.</p>

  <p>Low albumin in older adults is strongly associated with sarcopenia (muscle loss) through several mechanisms. Reduced albumin-bound hormone and nutrient transport impairs the delivery of anabolic signals to muscle tissue. Reduced oncotic pressure alters the fluid environment of muscle cells. And perhaps most importantly, low albumin in older adults almost always co-occurs with inadequate protein intake &#8212; the primary nutritional driver of sarcopenia.</p>

  <p>Albumin below 4.0 g/dL in adults over 65 predicts a dramatically increased risk of falls, hospitalization, surgical complications, slow recovery from illness, and nursing home admission. It is one of the components of several validated frailty indices because it so reliably captures the accumulated physiological burden of aging, malnutrition, and disease.</p>

  <p>The intervention message for older adults is straightforward: protein intake adequate to maintain albumin above 4.5 g/dL is a high-priority longevity intervention. Current evidence supports 1.6&#8211;2.2 g of protein per kg of body weight per day in active older adults &#8212; substantially above conventional dietary recommendations of 0.8 g/kg that are based on minimum requirements to prevent deficiency, not to optimize longevity.</p>
</section>

<section class="bm-section">
  <h2>How to Optimize Albumin</h2>

  <p>The primary levers for maintaining optimal albumin are protein nutrition, inflammation control, and protection of liver and kidney function.</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Adequate dietary protein:</strong> Albumin synthesis requires sufficient amino acid supply. Regular consumption of high-quality complete proteins &#8212; meat, fish, eggs, dairy, or complemented plant proteins &#8212; at 1.6&#8211;2.2 g/kg/day provides the substrate for hepatic albumin production.</li>
    <li><strong>Manage chronic inflammation:</strong> Because IL-6 and other inflammatory cytokines suppress albumin gene transcription, reducing the chronic inflammatory burden (through metabolic health optimization, anti-inflammatory diet, adequate sleep, and exercise) is essential. If hsCRP is chronically elevated, addressing its cause will typically improve albumin in parallel.</li>
    <li><strong>Liver health:</strong> The liver is the exclusive site of albumin synthesis. Minimizing alcohol, managing metabolic syndrome, avoiding hepatotoxic medications where possible, and maintaining healthy body composition all support hepatic albumin production capacity.</li>
    <li><strong>Kidney function:</strong> Proteinuria &#8212; albumin loss in the urine &#8212; reduces serum albumin and signals kidney damage. If albumin is low and urine protein is elevated, kidney function evaluation and blood pressure optimization are priorities.</li>
    <li><strong>Treat malabsorption:</strong> Conditions that impair protein absorption (celiac disease, inflammatory bowel disease, gastric achlorhydria, gut dysbiosis) reduce amino acid availability for albumin synthesis despite adequate dietary intake.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

